&lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/cybernetic-postliberalism/>
  rdf:type schema:WebPage ;
  schema:url &lt;https://emsenn.net/library/domains/humanities/domains/sociology/domains/cybernetic-postliberalism/> ;
  schema:name "Cybernetic Postliberalism" ;
  schema:description "An analytical sociology of how late-liberal governance reproduces itself on a contracting energetic substrate by formatting its constitutive contradictions as personally manageable affect, distributing that formatting through platformal feedback architecture, and absorbing every coherent subject-position — including those that name themselves as outsides — back into its metabolism." ;
  schema:datePublished "2026-03-03" ;
  schema:dateModified "2026-03-03" ;
  emsenn:Centralthesis "Liberal subjectivity is reproduced not through ideology or coercion but through cybernetic feedback loops between bodies, affect, technology, and economy — made operative at planetary scale by platforms — under conditions of declining net energy that have collapsed the institutional surplus once funding centralized abstraction. The process named californication (structural contradictions formatted as personally manageable affect) is recurrent across the modern pastoral apparatus — its prior institutional form was the Christian church — and has intensified now because the energetic buffers that supported richer institutional interiors have contracted." ;
  emsenn:Closureclaim "The circuits are exhaustive. No coherent subject-position produces an outside; anarchist refusal, primitivist exit, accelerationist hyperengagement, abolitionist construction, melancholic critique, and spiritual transcendence are genres within the same metabolism, each producing affective material the system requires. The framework is totalitarian as description, not as politics." ;
